	     <table class=mform  border=0 cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0 width=100%>
	     <form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100029837645773>
	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=>RE: Group combat</a> <a id=fs8 href=#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Wed, Sep 12th 8:39 AM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=52070><span id= >Tinywulf</span></a><br><span id=notbold>12 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [5.00]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I have to disagree with part of this as well.&nbsp;&nbsp;Most of these tactics seem to be mid to low level with an emphasis on smaller groups.<br><br>And also a correction to add.  Enchanters get an 11pt damage shield.  By lvl 39 you'll be using a 16pt damage shield and I think the druid 49 is a 21pt damage shield?  Not sure there, can't remember.  The Magician does indeed have a better damage shield, but our's is a very close second.<br><br>As to the druid being the puller.  I can only see this happening at higher levels if you are solo or in small groups that have some sort of deficit (Like no night sight, etc, although group wolf would give anyone infra).  Your mana is way too valuable to run around and not med.  If you are not casting then you are wasting resources.  In the lower to mid-level game you will find you can run up and melee mobs with your damage shield on and do rather well.  That works all the way up to about lvl 35.  Try meleeing a chicken over in Dreadlands :(  It's humiliating.  My weaponskill is maxed and I wiff so many times its pitiful.  Your HP, your AC and yoru ATK will just not stay up to par.  Once your in the 40's you'll be saying, "Melee?  What's that?"<br><br>Your dots also will be of questionable use.  In a normal setting, where you are not taking on named mobs or extreamly high hp mobs, you'll find that a group of 5 or 6 with 3 melee's will be mowing mobs down fast enough that your dots are a waste.  You'll either be a full healer/buffer or a healer/nuker or a full healer depending on who is in your group at any one given time.  Your DoT's are still very powerful and valuable, especially over in Vellious.  Those giants have horrific amounts of hit points, so you'll probably get the bang for you buck there.<br><br>One other note i'd like to pass on where we excell at.....root.  Forget about loading your highest root.  Stick to the lowest level root you have, the one that does 10dmg.  It has a very low mana cost, holds as long as the higher level roots and is invaluable for crowd control when you don't have a chanter.  Your tank got an add?  Target one incoming and root it, add snare and be ready before it breaks.  With a little practice you can keep that mob out of play till your group is ready for it.  Your cleric getting nailed by a mob?  Throw in the grasping roots to give him a breather so that he can back off and heal up.  The only drawback to that spell is the damage component.  Because it damages it can break chanter mez's, which will get you slapped silly if you endanger your chanter with it.  However, you'll recieve kisses galore if you get the mob off her long enough for her to get back to work.<br><br>Root parking is one of our best assets in my opinion and it can make up for missing skill sets in a lot of groupings.<br><br>But mainly, until you reach the 50's..in a group you are going to start feeling inadequate.  You warrior will be down a bar and a half of life in a bad pull in the first couple of seconds.  So you have to start your heals (Provided your the groups healer).  That barely holds the mobs damage at bay for that round.  Next two rounds are spent casting more heals to bring the tank back up and keep him at only missing a bar of health.  Thats three castings from you and about a bar of mana (at lvl 45). So now you med and then pop up to heal another tank a couple times and then med.  So the combat ends and you are down a bar and a half mana, two bars if it went really bad...and the group wants to pull again.  No one wants downtime.  You luck out and the second pull is an easy one, you only have to cast heal once.  Lucky for you at lvl 35 you get a natural boost to your mana regen, so now your only down a bar and a half of mana still and you've gone through 2 combats.  You can see the trend here.  Even with a group of six, melee heavy, taking single pulls, you are going to find your mana taxed if you are the only healer.  An enchanter or bard helps tremendously, but the fact is you will become very aware of how limited your healing is.  you can keep people up and going, but if you let a member get below half before you start healing...there is a chance you will loose that tank.  Depends on the mobs you fight, but your healing just can not recover the tanks hit points quickly enough in bad situations.<br><br>You'll also find that buffing just isn't what its cracked up to be at higher levels.  The lvl 44 clerical Resolution spell blows Skin like Diamond out of the water.  Likewise the Clerical Celestial healing at lvl 44 is an awesome tool for them, heals 700+ hp for 250 mana.  You can't afford not to use this if you have a cleric in the group...however it conflicts with Chloroplast.  So that spells out.  That leaves you Strength and SoW to cast as buffs, along with the possiblity of a damage shield.  Strength and SoW are long lasting, damage shields are shorter duration.  So in a group with a cleric you will find yourself doing a damage shield and then playing the part of nuker.  (Snare is a given, provided you don't have a necro in the group).<br>However, you are going to find nuking just a bit frustrating as well.  By level 44 you will find your best spell available to you does 444 dmg and has a HUGE recast time.  Your next best spell does 250dmg and is all or nothing resist and has a HUGE recast time.  Drop down one more and you have a 99dmg spell that has an instant recast time.  So if you wanted to nuke a mob out, you could do 690dmg then sit on your hands for a while waiting for an icon to light up so you can click.  So you have some major drawbacks as a druid in this area.  However, as you can see from what I wrote....you are definitly preferable to no healing at all.  you can be the primary healer in a group, provided they adjust their tactics a bit.  You can be the primary buffer in a group and do reasonably well.  you can be a nuker in a group and deliver quite a punch.  It's just full of limitations.  <br><br>Once you hit the 50's and get chloroblast, life will be much easier for you.  At least you can save your tanks life and stop feeling like you are a waste of a party member.  People will stop looking at you and sighing, thinking, "I wish you were a cleric."<br><br>But hey, them's the breaks.  It's the price we pay for being incredibly powerful from levels 1 to 35ish and again from lvls 50 to 60.  We have a great, non-skill based way to make decent money (ports) and we are not as equipment bound as other classes, a little Wis and a little +Mana and you're good to go.<br><br>Later,<br>Tinywulf of Veeshan</p>&nbsp;<br></td></td></tr>
